author: Tracy A Hicks
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on May 31, 2020
review_content: Most days, I'm sure I'm going to die due to insane headaches.I've tried homeopathic oils, herbs, even dancing naked in the yard under a full moon-all with no results.  I don't believe in modern medicine, so I haven't ever tried aspirin or  any other sort of pain relief before.I did try to dedicate my first-born to the devotion to Apollo (the God of medicine), but the kid kept being a teenager (ok, I started late on this course of treatment) and must have annoyed him, because well, headaches still here (as is the teenager).I looked on YouTube, and followed the instructions for the following ways to cure a headache (btw-none of them work):1. Massage your head with an electric toothbrush - while this felt nice, it did nothing for my headaches.2. Placing hair clips on your eyebrows - this one was painful, I don't recommend, and the headache was still there, along with pain around my eyebrows now.3. Ghee up your nose - this was just gross.4. Salt Herring & Elderberry leaves - I tried eating the herring, making tea from the leaves-nope, didn't work.So, imagine my surprise when I broke down and tried Tylenol.  30 minutes later-no headache!  It's a miracle!  Where has this stuff been all my life?  So crazy that I've been suffering for 50 years and suddenly I'm cured!I think I'll offer a bottle of this stuff up to Apollo-I'll be he's appreciate the heads up.
title: Tylenol is a Life Changer!

author: M Cox
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on November 15, 2020
review_content: Update:I suckered and bought this same product at Sam's Wholesale. The big sign with the price on it stated it was laser drilled and gel capsules.  I opened it when I got home and it was just the same old regular hard capsules and definitely NOT gel capsules.  And you won't find the words Laser Drilled anywhere on the bottle.  I want the ones that are advertised on television.  Laser drilled ones and a gel inside.  I think Amazon and Sam's are intentionally misleading people into buying a standard product that is advertised as being gel and laser drilled.  I haven't gone to Costco yet, but I suspect it's the same thing.  I will buy it and open it before I leave the store and break one in half to see what's inside.  But I'm not going to ever buy anything from the makers of Tylenol until I see the words laser drilled on the bottle itself.Until I see the words laser drilled on the bottle itself, I'm never going to purchase this product again. I have very severe neck pain and this doesn't do much for pain relief.  I have five of my 8 vertebrae fused together with a metal plate with ten screws. It hurts constantly even with oxycodone.The capsules I ordered are garden variety Tylenol and were NOT gel capsules.  There was no mention of being laser drilled on the box either.  Another person wrote this as well.  I am afraid to order them again for fear they are all hard as chalk and easily break in half with your fingers. I don't think you can snap a gel tab to snap in half. Don't believe it?  Just break it in half with your fingers.  Hard as chalk inside.  No gel whatsoever.I would be interested to know if anybody has tried to snap a capsule in half and see what they find inside.  I have absolutely none of these are gel caps and certainly not laser drilled.  Tylenol is supposed to start working in about 20 minutes.  Oxycodone takes 40 to 45 minutes to even begin to work.
title: NOT GEL capsules. Hard and easy to snap in half.
